Part 1

In this exercise, we will continue working on exchange rate data for your assigned country. You can consider the exchange rate against the US dollar which is made available by the IMF. To solve the exercise, go through the following steps.

  • Download the data and clean the dataset. Hint: Do you need to skip lines to access the column names? What is the separator between variables in your data? Try using read_table instead of read_csv.

  • Calculate the change in the natural logarithm of the exchange rate. Include this as a column in your dataset. What does \(\Delta e_t\) approximate? Hint: The following derivation might be helpful. \[\begin{equation} \Delta e_t = 100\times \left(\log(E_t) - \log(E_{t-1}) \right) \end{equation}\]

  • Reproduce the below plots for your assigned country.

  • Why did you choose this period?

  • What is measured by the exchange rate?

  • For what day did the exchange rate depreciate the most?

  • For what day did the exchange rate appreciate the most?

  • Which time series below are stationary? Which are non-stationary?
